The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) — at literary festivals and bookstores. They had every reason to celebrate.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a "symbol of resilience and endurance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven books, been translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight films based on the books have grossed $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
It is hard to imagine a day when global audiences are not captivated by Rowling's works, especially for a specific age group and those with a literary mindset.
Therefore, I am still amazed every time I recall my students' poor reaction to "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I included this work in the syllabus of my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "Bestsellers in American Literature" series course since 1993.
The course examines popular works from the 17th century up to the present, inviting students to think about why and how these bestsellers have attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask my students to choose a final work that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first "Harry Potter" novel.
That year, the Harry Potter fever hit the American coast hard.
In June, the American publisher of the series urgently released the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," in bookstores.
The institution also published the third book in the series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone."
By the end of that month, Rowling's novels had occupied the top three positions on The New York Times bestseller list, and the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" had topped the paperback books sales chart.
Time magazine even featured the glasses-wearing wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image is everywhere in sight.
My students were eager to know why such frenzy had occurred.
Oh my goodness, they were thoroughly disappointed.
In their view, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, not standing up to the classics of "The Chronicles of Narnia" or "The Lord of the Rings" that they cherished in their childhood memories.
Although their childhood had just passed a few years ago, they accused Harry Potter, like many notorious adult critics, of being "fabricated," "poorly written," "clichéd," and "boring."

In their view, Harry had neither miracles nor wit nor warmth.
The students' hostility surprised me, but in hindsight, there was nothing surprising about it.
Although adults had always been a significant part of the Harry Potter audience, these students were precisely at the wrong age to objectively appreciate the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They were past the age of accepting new children's literature, but at the same time too young to have their own children (at that time I had just had my own child), and they eagerly insisted that although the Harry series was now popular, it would soon be forgotten by people.
The following autumn, in 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" as their final analysis text, just like their predecessors, they confidently refused to accept this work.
Let's fast forward to spring 2007.
After setting the course aside for several years, I taught "Bestselling American Books" again.
When students chose their final analysis text, they chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone".
And I was prepared to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
These were a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first read Rowling's works not as university students, but as teenagers in their early teens, just entering adolescence. This meant that they grew up alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione as they became young adults.
The same thing happened again in the fall of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" had become a motto, not just a label.
Would Harry disappear from memory?
It is impossible as long as we are alive.
Since 2010, I have taught a bestseller course twice, and both times the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
Is it because they are tired of Potter?
Based on the reviews received for the Harry Potter series in another course I taught, "Children's Literature," where I taught Rowling's works, this seems unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not choose *Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone*, instead I chose *Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban* — which is my favorite among the seven Harry Potter novels, marking the series' transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, and it offers complex portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also loved this book the most.
But how long would the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books on the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban."
By 2012, this figure had risen to 94%.
But in the following years, the percentage continued to decline — 87% in 2014, and down to 81% in 2016.
These are not scientific figures, I know.
But I am curious: next spring, when I teach "Children's Literature" again, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is continuously declining and will never become a timeless classic?
Or is there a balancing point ahead, where the percentage can stabilize and stop declining?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I am glad to have always invited him into my classroom.
